# DS Storybook Testing

Use this rule when writing Storybook stories with interaction and a11y tests for Design System components.

## Location & imports

Stories live in `apps/storybook/src/stories/[name]/[name].stories.tsx`, separate from component source in `packages/ui`.

```ts
import type { Meta, StoryObj } from "@storybook/react-vite";
import { expect, userEvent, within } from "storybook/test";
import { Button } from "@ds-12/ui/button";
import { StoryCaption, StorySectionTitle } from "../../lib/story-presentation.tsx";
```

Use `@ds-12/ui/[name]` subpath imports. Storybook resolves these via the `@ds-12/ui` alias in `apps/storybook/.storybook/main.ts` (no per-component alias needed).

Extract large showcase renders (variant/size matrices, icon grids) into `[name]-story-fixtures.tsx` beside the story file. Keep stories focused on meta, args, and `play` functions.

## Global CSS in `.storybook`

Import global styles in `.storybook/main.ts`, not `preview.tsx`:

```ts
/// <reference path="./env.d.ts" />

import type { StorybookConfig } from "@storybook/react-vite";
import "./styles.css";
```

`env.d.ts` declares `*.css` modules for TypeScript. The `/// <reference path="./env.d.ts" />` directive is required so `vp check` passes when only `main.ts` is staged during pre-commit (TS2882 otherwise). Do not import CSS in `preview.tsx` — add new `.storybook` CSS imports to `main.ts` with the same reference.

## Setup (already configured)

Storybook 10 is configured in `apps/storybook/.storybook/main.ts`:

```ts
addons: [
  "@chromatic-com/storybook",
  "@storybook/addon-a11y",
  "@storybook/addon-docs",
  "@storybook/addon-mcp",
],
framework: "@storybook/react-vite",
```

Interaction tests use `play` functions with utilities from `storybook/test` (Storybook 10), not `@storybook/test`. Run them manually from the Storybook UI (Interactions panel); CI uses Chromatic for visual regression only.

A11y is enabled globally in `apps/storybook/.storybook/preview.tsx` with `a11y.test: "todo"`.

## Story file structure

Every component story file should include:

1. **Default** — single-instance story with a `play` function covering core interaction + a11y
2. **Showcase stories** — variant/size matrices imported from `[name]-story-fixtures.tsx`; add a `play` function when the showcase needs interaction or a11y coverage

Use `tags: ["autodocs"]` and `satisfies Meta<typeof Component>` on the meta object.

Bundle repeated single-instance plays via helpers in `apps/storybook/src/lib/component-tests.ts`:

```ts
export const Default: Story = {
  play: async (context) => {
    await createButtonA11yPlay("Button")(context);
    await createButtonKeyboardFocusPlay("Button")(context);
    await createButtonFocusVisiblePlay("Button")(context);
    await createButtonMouseClickPlay("Button")(context);
  },
};
```

For stateful components, wrap in a local helper (see `pagination.stories.tsx`):

```ts
function InteractivePagination({ page: initialPage = 1, ...props }: PaginationProps) {
  const [page, setPage] = useState(initialPage);
  return <Pagination {...props} page={page} onPageChange={setPage} />;
}
```

## Querying elements in play functions

Choose the query based on how many matching elements the story renders:

| Story type | Query | When |
|---|---|---|
| `Default` (args only) | `getByRole` | Exactly one instance |
| Matrix / showcase fixture | `getAllByRole` | Same label repeated per size row or column |

`getByRole` throws when multiple elements match. Matrix fixtures (e.g. `IconButtonMatrixTable`) render one control per size row, so the same accessible name appears multiple times.

**Single instance** — use `getByRole`:

```ts
const button = canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /button/i });
```

**Matrix / showcase** — use `getAllByRole`, assert the expected count, then spot-check one element:

```ts
export const ButtonWithIcon: Story = {
  render: () => <IconButtonMatrixTable buttons={leadingIconButtons} iconPosition="left" />,
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    const leadingButtons = canvas.getAllByRole("button", { name: "Download" });
    const trailingButtons = canvas.getAllByRole("button", { name: "Continue" });

    await expect(leadingButtons).toHaveLength(3); // lg, md, sm
    await expect(trailingButtons).toHaveLength(3);
    await expect(leadingButtons[0]).toHaveAccessibleName("Download");
    await expect(trailingButtons[0]).toHaveAccessibleName("Continue");
  },
};
```

When a matrix mixes states (e.g. one disabled icon button among several enabled), use `getAllByRole` then narrow with `.find()`:

```ts
const buttons = canvas.getAllByRole("button", { name: /add/i });
const disabledButton = buttons.find(
  (button) => button.getAttribute("aria-disabled") === "true",
);
```

For presentational showcase stories without a semantic role, use `getAllByText` (see `badge.stories.tsx` `TypesAndVariants`).

## Required interaction coverage

Apply the behaviors below on `Default` (bundled via `component-tests.ts` helpers) or on dedicated showcase stories. Skip behaviors that do not apply (e.g. skip disabled focus for non-interactive components like Divider or Skeleton).

### Interactive controls (Button, Chip, Input, Pagination, …)

#### 1. KeyboardFocus

Tab into the component and assert focus is received:

```ts
export const KeyboardFocus: Story = {
  args: { children: "Button" },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    const el = canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /button/i });

    await userEvent.tab();
    await expect(el).toHaveFocus();
  },
};
```

#### 2. FocusVisible

Keyboard focus triggers `data-focus-visible` (Base UI convention):

```ts
export const FocusVisible: Story = {
  args: { children: "Button" },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    const el = canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /button/i });

    await userEvent.tab();
    await expect(el).toHaveAttribute("data-focus-visible");
  },
};
```

#### 3. MouseClickNoFocusVisible

Mouse click does NOT trigger focus-visible:

```ts
export const MouseClickNoFocusVisible: Story = {
  args: { children: "Button" },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    const el = canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /button/i });

    await userEvent.click(el);
    await expect(el).not.toHaveAttribute("data-focus-visible");
  },
};
```

#### 4. Disabled

Base UI interactive components use `disabled` prop; assert the rendered disabled state. Disabled controls must remain keyboard-focusable:

```ts
export const DisabledInteraction: Story = {
  args: { disabled: true, children: "Button" },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    const el = canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /button/i });

    await expect(el).toHaveAttribute("aria-disabled", "true");
    await userEvent.tab();
    await expect(el).toHaveFocus();
  },
};
```

Use a distinct story name (`DisabledInteraction`) when a visual-only `Disabled` story already exists.

#### 5. AccessibleName

Component must have an accessible name resolvable by `getByRole` (single instance) or `getAllByRole` (matrix):

```ts
export const AccessibleName: Story = {
  args: { children: "Button" },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);

    await expect(
      canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /button/i }),
    ).toBeInTheDocument();
  },
};
```

Matrix showcase — pick a representative label and assert count + name:

```ts
export const LoadingState: Story = {
  render: () => <VariantSizeMatrixTable loading />,
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    const button = canvas.getAllByRole("button", { name: /loading/i })[0];

    await expect(button).toHaveAccessibleName("Loading");
    await expect(button).toHaveAttribute("aria-busy", "true");
    await expect(button).toHaveAttribute("aria-disabled", "true");
  },
};
```

Icon-only buttons need an explicit `aria-label` in args:

```ts
export const AccessibleName: Story = {
  args: { variant: "icon", "aria-label": "Add" },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    await expect(canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /add/i })).toBeInTheDocument();
  },
};
```

### Toggle components (Chip)

Chip uses Base UI `Button` with `aria-pressed`. Confirm the role before writing queries:

```ts
export const Toggle: Story = {
  args: { children: "Label", active: false },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    const chip = canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /label/i });

    await expect(chip).toHaveAttribute("aria-pressed", "false");
    await userEvent.click(chip);
    await expect(chip).toHaveAttribute("aria-pressed", "true");
  },
};
```

For checkbox-pattern toggles, use `getByRole("checkbox")` and `toBeChecked()` instead.

### Non-interactive / presentational components (Divider, Skeleton, Typography, Badge)

Skip focus/disabled stories. Assert semantic structure instead:

```ts
// Skeleton — status role + accessible name
export const AccessibleName: Story = {
  args: { "aria-label": "Loading" },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    await expect(canvas.getByRole("status", { name: /loading/i })).toBeInTheDocument();
  },
};

// Divider — separator role
export const AccessibleStructure: Story = {
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    await expect(canvas.getByRole("separator")).toBeInTheDocument();
  },
};
```

### Composite components (InputField, TextareaField)

Test the primary interactive element inside the field wrapper:

```ts
export const KeyboardFocus: Story = {
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    const input = canvas.getByRole("textbox", { name: /label/i });

    await userEvent.tab();
    await expect(input).toHaveFocus();
  },
};
```

## Rules

- Use `getByRole` with `name` option for single-instance stories; use `getAllByRole` when matrix fixtures render duplicate names — never query by class or test-id unless no semantic role exists
- Do NOT assert CSS class names — assert behavior and ARIA attributes
- Do NOT assert visual styles (color, spacing) — that belongs to visual regression (Chromatic)
- Always confirm the component's rendered role and instance count before choosing `getByRole` vs `getAllByRole`
- Keep showcase renders in `[name]-story-fixtures.tsx`; attach `play` functions to showcase stories that need interaction or a11y checks
- Run interaction tests from the Storybook UI (Interactions panel)
